## 22. DevOps Requirements

The Patient Management module requires:

* PostgreSQL database
* Flyway migrations
* S3 bucket or approved object storage
* IAM permissions for secure document upload and download
* Secrets Manager configuration
* CloudWatch application logs
* Backup policies
* S3 encryption and versioning
* File-size and file-type restrictions
* Malware-scanning strategy for uploaded documents in future
* Development, QA and production configuration

No patient information should be stored in environment variables or deployment manifests.

---

## 23. QA Test Scenarios

Minimum test scenarios:

1. Patient self-registers successfully
2. Reception creates a patient successfully
3. Duplicate mobile number is detected
4. Similar name and date of birth produce a warning
5. Authorized user searches patient
6. Unauthorized user cannot access patient
7. Clinic A cannot access Clinic B patient
8. Patient views own profile
9. Patient cannot edit clinical fields
10. Reception updates contact details
11. Doctor views permitted clinical history
12. Lab user receives limited information
13. Patient document uploads successfully
14. Unauthorized document download is blocked
15. Patient status change is audited
16. Invalid date of birth is rejected
17. Invalid mobile number is rejected
18. Pagination works correctly
19. Timeline returns events in correct order
20. Inactive patient behavior follows business rules

---

## 24. Acceptance Criteria

The module will be accepted when:

* Patients can register through the patient portal.
* Reception can create patient records.
* Authorized users can search patients.
* Duplicate patients are identified before creation.
* Every patient receives a unique patient number.
* Patient profiles display only role-permitted information.
* Patient timelines show related healthcare events.
* Patients can view their own records.
* Patients cannot modify clinical information.
* Clinic users cannot access another clinic’s patients.
* All sensitive changes are audited.
* Documents are stored securely.
* APIs match the OpenAPI specification.
* Frontend and backend integration passes QA.
* Database migrations deploy successfully.
* Performance meets agreed non-functional requirements.

---

## 25. Non-Functional Requirements

### Performance

* Patient search target: under 1 second for normal clinic volumes
* Patient profile target: under 2 seconds
* Timeline target: under 3 seconds
* Paginated queries required for large datasets

### Availability

The patient module should meet the platform availability objective defined in the BRD.

### Scalability

The module should support increasing numbers of clinics and patient records without requiring a redesign of the core data model.

### Usability

Patient registration should be possible within approximately two minutes when complete information is available.

### Accessibility

Forms and navigation should follow accepted web-accessibility practices.

---

## 26. Dependencies

The Patient Management module depends on:

* Authentication and Tenant Onboarding
* Role and Permission Management
* Clinic configuration
* PostgreSQL
* Object storage
* Audit logging
* Notification service for selected events

Other modules depending on Patient Management include:

* Appointments
* Consultations
* Prescriptions
* Laboratory
* Billing
* Payments
* Reports
* Analytics
* Future AI services

---

## 27. Risks and Mitigations

| Risk                         | Mitigation                                                   |
| ---------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------ |
| Duplicate patient records    | Duplicate detection and manual confirmation                  |
| Incorrect patient selected   | Display patient number, DOB and mobile confirmation          |
| Cross-clinic data exposure   | Tenant filtering, authorization tests and security logging   |
| Incomplete registration data | Required fields and validation                               |
| Sensitive data in logs       | Structured masking and logging standards                     |
| Unauthorized profile changes | RBAC and audit logging                                       |
| Unsafe document uploads      | File validation, private storage and future malware scanning |
| Slow patient search          | Indexing, pagination and optimized queries                   |

---

## 28. Definition of Ready

Development may begin when:

* User stories are approved
* Business rules are approved
* Figma screens are available
* API contract is reviewed
* Database changes are reviewed
* Role permissions are confirmed
* Acceptance criteria are clear
* Dependencies are identified

---

## 29. Definition of Done

The module is complete when:

* Frontend screens are implemented
* Backend APIs are implemented
* OpenAPI documentation is updated
* Database migrations are included
* Tenant isolation is tested
* Role restrictions are tested
* Audit logging is implemented
* Unit and integration tests pass
* QA test cases pass
* Dev environment deployment succeeds
* Product owner accepts the demo

---

